title: UI Engineer
description: Develop an interactive responsive website using HTML, CSS,JavaScript and its modern Frameworks.
question: What you need to know before you get started with UI Engineer?
answer: UI Engineer is also known as User Interface Engineer whose job is to think from the user perspective and to design websites and web applications that are attractive and extremely functional.

skillsList.name: HTML
skillsList.description: HTML is known as HyperText Markup Language which is the building block of programming languages. It contains documents that are designed to display in a web browser with the help of Html tags.

topicList.name: Create first web page
topicList.description:
For the creation of web pages by using the HTML, developers use different kinds of text editors like Visual Studio Code, Atom, Sublime Text, Vim or Bracket that help to set up complex sites. In this session, we will be using Sublime Text as a text editor.

Initially, it's important to create a document and to check whether it reflects in the browsers. There are different kinds of browsers available in the network platform such as Firefox, Google Chrome, Edge, Opera, Safari etc. Throughout the sessions, we will be using Google Chrome as a browser.

topicList.name: Create an HTML element
topicList.description:
The building bricks of HTML are called tags. For example, considering tags as Lego, in which the studs get neatly wedged in between the tubes in the top section and the bottom and sides of every brick making them stick together firmly. 

The same property plays the HTML tags, which contain three parts as opening tag “<tagname>”, content and closing tag “</tagname>”  which shows the browser how to display the contents.

For example: <tagname>Hello World</tagname>

topicList.name: HTML Versions
topicList.description:
The first HTML was released in 1991 by Tim Berners-Lee. His creation has seen many updates ever since, including HTML 2.0 in 1995, HTML 3.2 in 1997, HTML 4.01 in 1999, and XHTML in 2000. Currently, the newest HTML version is HTML5 which was released in 2014.

HTML5 is the latest version of HTML programming that allows better management of the web application or the website contents which introduces new semantic elements that make writing markup substantially easier and cleaner.

topicList.name: HTML tag
topicList.description: The HTML tag is represented as “<html> and </html>”, function as the root of an HTML document and also acts as a container for all other HTML elements. All the contents should be written within the “html” tag.

topicList.name: Head tag
topicList.description:
The head tag in the HTML is used to define the head portion of the HTML document which contains title, links, images etc. The head tag is mainly defined as the tag which carries additional information to the web page. 

For example: This can be easily seen when you share a link through Whatsapp. At that time Whatsapp goes to these tags and looks for an image to show.

topicList.name: Title tag
topicList.description:
The title tag is used to display or represents the title of the document which is shown in the browser's title bar or in the page's tab.

Example : <html>
		<head>
			<title>My Website Title</title>
		</head>
	</html>

topicList.name: Body tag
topicList.description:
After the title is presented, it's now to display the contents into the html document by using tag. The tag is also known as visible part of the document which keeps other html tags like
,
,

etc.

topicList.name: Heading
topicList.description: The text header of an HTML document is categorized to h1, h2, h3, h4, h5 and h6 in one of six different sizes depending upon the priorities. Where <h1> head tag defines as a high priority tag with the largest text size, and <h6> tag is defined as the least priority head tag with smaller text size.

topicList.name: Paragraph
topicList.description:
The

tag is used to define the paragraph of the HTML document in which it does not have a specified priority. Example :

Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Mauris sagittis eu lorem sed feugiat. Cras iaculis tellus metus. Cras vel gravida arcu, id hendrerit leo. Donec massa lectus, gravida vel eros eget, imperdiet sagittis risus. Morbi volutpat sem a gravida pulvinar. Sed nibh turpis, dictum ut tempor eu, rutrum eget metus.

topicList.name: Parent child relationship
topicList.description:
For a well-written code, consistent indentation and spacing pattern (parent-child relationship) must be followed while writing code. Instead, if you are following an inconsistency and spacing it will cause difficulty to read and understand the code. 

The below given is the example for a well structured parent-child relationship :
       <html>
		<head>
			<title>Hello World</title>
		</head>
	</html>

topicList.name: Comments
topicList.description:
The comments in the HTML are written as “<!-- comments -->" and are ignored by any web browsers. Adding comments in HTML documents helps to understand the codes to others and increase code readability. 
Example : <html>
		        <head>  <!-- Document header starts -->
			        <title>Hello World</title>
		        </head>  <!-- Document header ends -->
	           </html>

topicList.name: Adding Link
topicList.description: For creating a link to the webpage we need to use the <a> tag commonly known as anchor tag that carries additional information known as attributes.

topicList.name: Attributes
topicList.description:
HTML attributes are a modifier of an HTML element type. An attribute either modifies the default functionality of an element type or provides functionality to certain element types, unable to function correctly without them. 

The <a> tag is commonly used with the href attribute for creating a link. By clicking on the link it will direct to its respective page on the same page. Instead, you can open the given link in another tab which you will learn in the next topic.

topicList.name: Multiple attributes
topicList.description:
Multiple attributes can be used in an element. A link can be open in a new tab by using an attribute target=”_blank”. A blank attribute defines to open the document in another tab. The other target attributes that can be used are self, _self and blank.

Another attribute title specifies additional information about an element. The value of the title attribute will be displayed when the mouse hovers over that element. Also, multiple attributes must be separated by a space. 

Note: 
i. Duplication of an attribute is not allowed in the same element.
ii. No order preference among multiple attributes.

topicList.name: Attribute categorization
topicList.description:
Attributes are required for the HTML tags to work properly. The attributes are categorised under two types namely Specific or Global attributes and Mandatory or Optional attributes.

a. Specific or Global attributes
i. Specific attributes are the type of attributes which are specific for some tags only.
Example: href attribute is specific for anchor tag, it will not work for other tags.

ii. Global attributes can be used for any HTML element.
Example: Attribute title

b. Mandatory or Optional attributes 
i. A mandatory attribute is defined as a required element. 
Example: Anchor tag needs href attribute to open a link.

ii. Whereas an optional attribute is defined as an optional element.
Example: title and target attributes are optional for the anchor tag.

topicList.name: Attribute values
topicList.description:
The attribute has two parts: name and value. The values of some attributes have multiple choices. 

To make it more clear take one of the attribute value “href” which we have learned from the previous lesson which accepts any links or other web pages. Whereas “target” doesn’t have the privilege to accept other values rather than self, _self, blank, _blank. And in the case of titles, it also accepts any kind of texts.

topicList.name: Custom attribute
topicList.description:
These attributes are user built attributes. The attribute’s value is pre-defined. Users can define the attribute name and value for storing additional information. We can embed custom data attributes on all HTML elements. The custom attributes prefixed with “data-”. The attribute values can be any string. Example:

Hello World

topicList.name: Image tag
topicList.description: The img tag is used to add images on the webpages. The src attribute is used to tell the browser where to find the image file. Also, the alt attribute is used to act as an alternative description for the image when the image is not displayed.

topicList.name: Absolute path method
topicList.description: In this Topic, we are learning shortcuts in Sublime text editor.

topicList.name: How to construct a tag?
topicList.description: Before creating a tag we should recall in our mind about the following questions: a. What is the tag name and purpose of the tag? b. Whether it needs content or not? c. Mandatory attributes are present or not? d. Optional attributes required or not? For answering these questions, it might be easy to explain and understand through an example, so let us consider an anchor tag. The tag name is and the purpose is to link from one page to another. It needs content because it defines a hyperlink and also as it is a paired tag, the content will be placed within the opening and closing of the anchor tag. Example : My Link href is a mandatory attribute that is required as it parsed as a bookmark on the web page. Example : My Link. Optional attributes are required for giving it a title when hovers the My Link Example : My Link

topicList.name: Group tags
topicList.description:
Group tags are defined to group the HTML elements which means it acts as a list that carries pieces of information. There are three different kinds of lists :
a. Unordered list <ul>
b. Ordered list <ol>
c. Definition list <dl>

topicList.description:
The unordered list starts with the

topicList.description:
The ordered list starts with the

topicList.name: Introduction to table
topicList.description:
The HTML table allows the developers to arrange data into rows and columns of cells using tag. Each row in the table is defined with a tag and a
tag is used to create data cells. Table headings are used to represent the actual data cells defined with the tag. Also in order to put borders across all cells a border attribute is used along with a tag. Example :
Name Class Division
Name1 10 A

topicList.name: Grouping table rows
topicList.description: The HTML table consists with three main elements namely <tbody>, <thead> and <tfoot>. The <tbody> tag is used to group the body content in the HTML table. The <thead> tag is used to group the header content of the HTML table and <tfoot> tag is used to group footer content in the HTML table.

topicList.name: Class and ID
topicList.description:
How class and id differ from each other, I). The id attribute defines a unique id or value for an HTML element Example :

Hello World

ii). The class attribute defines one or more classes for an HTML element. Example :

Hi

Hi

topicList.name: Forms
topicList.description:
When you want to collect data HTML forms are required. For that <form> tags are used to create HTML forms. There are two attributes for form tags namely action and method.
Action attribute is performed when a form is submitted. Whereas Method attribute specifies when submitting the form data either as GET or POST method.

Sectioning tags or grouping tags specify the mentioning of different HTML elements in different areas. The grouping tags are

topicList.name: Inline and Block
topicList.description:
Every element in the HTML is categorized under inline or block element type depending upon the width of each element . Example :

Hello

Hello

topicList.name: Inline Element
topicList.description:
Inline elements start on a new line and take up only the necessary width. Roles of inline elements : a. Inline element width specifies it's exact sentence width. b. Inline element height specifies it's exact sentence height. c. Inline elements can be placed only with another inline. element. Example :

Hello

topicList.name: Block elements
topicList.description:
Block elements start on a new line, take up full width for it's content and end on a new line. The block elements are further categorised under Primary block elements and Secondary block elements. 

a. Secondary block element 
The block elements which accepts it's child as inline are known as secondary block elements
Rules:
A secondary block element can contain only inline elements.

b. Primary block element 
Primary block elements accept it's child as it is.
Rules:
A primary block element can contain the following elements:
Primary block elements
Secondary block elements
Inline elements

topicList.name: Picture tag
topicList.description: Picture tag is used to display images. The most common use of the element will be for art direction in responsive designs. The element has the following attributes: srcset (required) - defines the URL of the image to show media - accepts any valid media The element is required as the last child tag of the declaration block.

topicList.name: Audio tag
topicList.description:
Audio tag <audio> specify sound or music or other audio streams. There are different types of attributes for audio tag :
a. Controls - The audio can be controlled by play/pause or volume adjustment.
b. Muted - Specifies that the audio output should be muted.
c. Loop - Specifies that the audio will start over again, every time it is finished.
d. src - Specifies the URL of the audio file.

topicList.name: Video tag
topicList.description:
Video tag is used to pecifies video, such as a movie clip or other video streams. There are different kinds of attributes for video tags, listed below:
a. Controls - The video can be controlled by the play/pause button.
b. Width - Sets the width of the video player
c. Loop - Specifies that the video will start over again, every time it is finished.
d. Muted - Specifies that the audio output of the video should be muted
e. Autoplay - Specifies that the video will start playing as soon as it is ready
f. Src - Specifies the URL of the video file

topicList.name: Favicon
topicList.description:
Inorder to give a favicon for the website a link relation tag must be used to specify the relationship between the current document and the linked document/resource.
Example : <link rel= “icon” href= “images.png” sizes= “500x500” />

topicList.name: Meta tag
topicList.description:
Meta tag <meta> is used to provide information about the data in the HTML document. The metadata is used by browsers to display the content and by search engines to search the keywords. The meta description or content must be always below 140 characters.
Example : <meta name= “description” content= “HTML Tutorials” />

skillsList.name: Cascading Style Sheets
skillsList.description: Cascading Style Sheets also known as CSS describes how the elements should be displayed on the screen and it is perfectly stored in the css files.

lessonsList.name: Introduction to CSS
lessonsList.description: For describing the presentation of a document written in a markup language like HTML a style sheet language is used known as Cascading Style Sheets, which shortly named as CSS. In this lesson, you will know CSS from basic to advance level.

topicList.name: Introduction
topicList.description:
Cascading styling sheet (CSS) is a language that describes the style of an HTML document. CSS describes how HTML elements should be displayed. It can be applied in three ways. 
a. As an attribute
b. As a tag inside the head
c. As an external stylesheet method.

topicList.name: Writing the first style
topicList.description: Here we are styling a HTML element by attribute method. The style is written inside the opening tag as an attribute. Inside the attribute property and it’s value is written.

topicList.name: Inpage Method
topicList.description: The inpage method style is written as a tag inside the head. It is written as additional information to the web page. By this method we can style  multiple tags without repeating the style.

topicList.name: External stylesheet method
topicList.description: An external stylesheet file is linked to all web pages and all the styles are written inside this one stylesheet. The advantage of this method is we can style multiple web pages without repeating the code.

lessonsList.name: Selectors
lessonsList.description: A selector is an HTML tag in which the styles are applied. These style rules are then interrupted by the browsers and then applied to the corresponding elements in the HTML document. In this lesson, you will learn different kinds off selectors and their functions.

topicList.name: Class selector
topicList.description: The class selector selects elements with a specific class attribute. To select elements with a specific class, write a period (.) character, followed by the name of the class. You can also specify that only specific HTML elements should be affected by a class. To do this, start with the element name, then write the period (.) character, followed by the name of the class.

topicList.name: Id selector
topicList.description: The id selector uses the id attribute of an HTML element to select a specific element. The id of an element is unique within a page, so the id selector is used to select one unique element! To select an element with a specific id, write a hash (#) character, followed by the id of the element.

topicList.name: CSS combinators
topicList.description:
A combinator is something that explains the relationship between the selectors.A CSS selector can contain more than one simple selector. Between the simple selectors, we can include a combinator. There are four different combinators in CSS.
a. descendant selector (space)
b. child selector (>)
c. adjacent sibling selector (+)
d. general sibling selector (~)

topicList.name: Specificity
topicList.description: If there are two or more conflicting CSS rules that point to the same element, the browser follows some rules to determine which one is most specific and therefore wins out. Think of specificity as a score/rank that determines which style declarations are ultimately applied to an element.The universal selector (*) has low specificity, while ID selectors are highly specific!

topicList.name: Important
topicList.description: Important property in CSS means that all subsequent rules on an element are to be ignored, and the rule denoted by ! important is to be applied. This rule overrides all previous styling rules ​-- the ! important property increases its priority.

topicList.name: Universal selector
topicList.description: CSS universal selector selects all types of elements in an HTML page. An asterisk ( i.e. "*" ) is used to denote a CSS universal selector. This is useful when you want to set a style for all the elements of an HTML page.

topicList.name: Comma separated
topicList.description: A comma-separated list of selectors represents the union of all elements selected by each of the individual selectors in the list. For example, in CSS when several selectors share the same declarations, they may be grouped into a comma-separated list.

lessonsList.name: Decorating Tags
lessonsList.description: As we have learned in the previous lessons CSS is used style the web document using it's style rules that are applied along with the elements. In order to style the document, CSS uses different tags to give the web page more presentable such as color, background color, text decorations, and background images.

topicList.name: Colors
topicList.description: Element decorators are used to decorate tags in HTML. Here we are discussing color. Colors are specified using predefined color names, or RGB, HEX, HSL, RGBA, HSLA values.

topicList.name: Background color
topicList.description: The background color property sets the background color of an element.The background of an element is the total size of the element, including padding and border (but not the margin).

topicList.name: Background image
topicList.description: The background-image property sets one or more background images for an element.By default, a background-image is placed at the top-left corner of an element, and repeated both vertically and horizontally. In order to adjust position, repeat property and size of the background, we can use background property instead of background-image.

topicList.name: Text decoration
topicList.description: We can adjust size, weight, font style of texts using properties ‘font-size’, ‘font-weight’, ‘font-style’.

lessonsList.name: Box Models
lessonsList.description: There is a default layout scheme in every element in the HTML document, which is treated as a rectangular box by the CSS. In order to maintain texts, images or other media contents into this layout we use various properties of box model such as width, height, padding, margin, border, outline, border-radius and overflow.

topicList.name: Width
topicList.description: The width property sets the width of an element.The width of an element does not include padding, borders, or margins. The min-width and max-width properties override the width property.

topicList.name: Height
topicList.description: The height property sets the height of an element. The height of an element does not include padding, borders, or margins. If height: auto; the element will automatically adjust its height to allow its content to be displayed correctly. If height is set to a numeric value (like pixels, (r)em, percentages) then if the content does not fit within the specified height, it will overflow. How the container will handle the overflowing content is defined by the overflow property. The min-height and max-height properties override the height property.

topicList.name: Padding
topicList.description:
The CSS padding properties are used to generate space around an element's content, inside of any defined borders. With CSS, you have full control over the padding. There are properties for setting the padding for each side of an element (top, right, bottom, and left). CSS has properties for specifying the padding for each side of an element:
i. Padding-top
ii. Padding-right
iii. Padding-bottom
iv. Padding-left

topicList.name: Margin
topicList.description: The CSS margin properties are used to create space around elements, outside of any defined borders.With CSS, you have full control over the margins. There are properties for setting the margin for each side of an element (top, right, bottom, and left).

topicList.name: Border
topicList.description: The CSS border properties allow you to specify the style, width, and color of an element's border.The CSS box-sizing property allows us to include the padding and border in an element's total width and height.

topicList.name: Outline
topicList.description: An outline is a line that is drawn around elements, OUTSIDE the borders, to make the element "stand out".

topicList.name: Border radius
topicList.description: The border-radius property defines the radius of the element's corners.  This property allows you to add rounded corners to elements.

topicList.name: Overflow
topicList.description:
The overflow property specifies whether to clip the content or to add scrollbars when the content of an element is too big to fit in the specified area.The overflow property has the following values:

i. visible - Default. The overflow is not clipped. The content renders outside the element's box
ii. hidden - The overflow is clipped, and the rest of the content will be invisible
iii. scroll - The overflow is clipped, and a scrollbar is added to see the rest of the content
iv. auto - Similar to scroll, but it adds scrollbars only when necessary

lessonsList.name: Units
lessonsList.description: As we know CSS is comprised of style rules it also supports a number of measurement units including absolute units such as inches, centimetres, points, and so on, as well as relative measures such as percentages and em units. When specifying measurements in the style rules you need to use these values.

topicList.name: Absolute units
topicList.description: The absolute length units are fixed and a length expressed in any of these will appear as exactly that size. Absolute length units are not recommended for use on screen, because screen sizes vary so much. However, they can be used if the output medium is known, such as for print layout. Absolute units are cm, mm, in, px, pt, pc .

topicList.name: Relative units
topicList.description: Relative length units specify a length relative to another length property. Relative length units scale better between different rendering mediums. Relative units are em, ex, ch, rem, vw, vh, vmin, vmax, % .

topicList.name: Placing an element in horizontally center
topicList.description: If you would like to center align an element horizontally with respect to the parent element you can use the CSS margin property with the value auto for the left and right side, i.e. set the style rule margin: 0 auto; for the element. The auto value automatically adjusts the left and right margin and horizontally center aligned the element's block box.

lessonsList.name: Display
lessonsList.description: In the previous lesson, we have learnt every element in the HTML document has a rectangular box as a default layout. The display property in the CSS determines just how that rectangular box behaves. As the name suggests, this property is used to define the display of the different parts of a web page.

topicList.name: Inline and block
topicList.description: If we display an element as display: inline; the element stays in the same line and only takes up the width of its content on the other hand if we display the element as display: block; the element starts in a new line and takes up the whole available width.

topicList.name: Inline block
topicList.description: If we display an element as display: inline-block ; the element is displayed as an inline element but can be styled as a block level element.

topicList.name: Hide an element
topicList.description: We can hide an element by three ways in css. They are via display: none; or via visibility: hidden; or via opacity: 0;

lessonsList.name: Alignment
lessonsList.description: CSS provides several properties of the alignment for the elements and contents in the HTML document by using the text-align property or the vertical-align property.

topicList.name: Text align
topicList.description: The text-align property specifies the horizontal alignment of text in an element. We can align the element in left, center, right using text-align property.

topicList.name: Vertical align
topicList.description: The vertical-align property sets the vertical alignment of an element.

lessonsList.name: Custom Font
lessonsList.description: To make your web page more presentable you can add custom fonts to your CSS styles either by installing google fonts or you can load the fonts directly to the CSS files by using its link.

topicList.name: Install font using google fonts
topicList.description: To install google fonts you can go to the google fonts website by using the link - https://fonts.google.com/ . After selecting the font you need, you can attach the given code into the <head> of your HTML document. After, you should specify in CSS by using ‘font-family’ property.

topicList.name: Load downloaded font
topicList.description:
One way you can change the style of a document is by adding a new text font.To add a font, you need to download and install the font. Fonts come as files, and there are many sites on the Internet where you can download free fonts.  

In this topic you will learn to download and load the fonts. You can apply differents as per your needs in the CSS.

lessonsList.name: Positional Elements
lessonsList.description: CSS helps you to position your HTML element. You can put any HTML element at whatever location you like. You can specify whether you want the element positioned relative to its natural position in the page or absolute based on its parent element.

topicList.name: Element arrangement
topicList.description: An HTML document is also a three dimensional plane with X-axis, Y-axis and Z-axis. In this topic, we will learn how the elements in the HTML document are arranged with a demonstration.

topicList.name: Position relative
topicList.description:
The position property specifies the type of positioning method used for an element. There are five different position values.
i. static
ii. relative
iii. fixed
iv. absolute
v. sticky
An element with position: relative; is positioned relative to its normal position.Setting the top, right, bottom, and left properties of a relatively-positioned element will cause it to be adjusted away from its normal position. Other content will not be adjusted to fit into any gap left by the element.

topicList.name: Z- index
topicList.description: The z-index property specifies the stack order of an element. An element with greater stack order is always in front of an element with a lower stack order. Note: z-index only works on positioned elements (position: absolute, position: relative, position: fixed, or position: sticky).

topicList.name: Position absolute
topicList.description: An element with position: absolute; is positioned relative to the nearest positioned ancestor (instead of positioned relative to the viewport, like fixed). However; if an absolute positioned element has no positioned ancestors, it uses the document body, and moves along with page scrolling. Note: A "positioned" element is one whose position is anything except static.

topicList.name: Position fixed
topicList.description: An element with position: fixed; is positioned relative to the viewport, which means it always stays in the same place even if the page is scrolled. The top, right, bottom, and left properties are used to position the element. A fixed element does not leave a gap in the page where it would normally have been located.

topicList.name: Position sticky
topicList.description: An element with position: sticky; is positioned based on the user's scroll position. A sticky element toggles between relative and fixed, depending on the scroll position. It is positioned relative until a given offset position is met in the viewport - then it "sticks" in place (like position:fixed).

lessonsList.name: CSS Function
lessonsList.description: CSS functions are used to give values for CSS properties. In this lesson, you will learn about calc(), variables, linear gradients and radial gradients.

topicList.name: Calc
topicList.description: The calc() is used as a property value to perform calculation in CSS by using the operators + - * / .

topicList.name: Linear Gradient
topicList.description: The Linear Gradient allows smooth color transitions. It required a minimum of two colors for it's gradient transition from top, down, left and right.

topicList.name: Radial Gradient
topicList.description: A Radial Gradient element requires a minimum two colors but what it differs from a linear gradient is that the first color starts at the centre position and fades to the end color towards the edge of the element.

topicList.name: CSS Variables
topicList.description: CSS variables or custom properties are entities that contain specific values that can be reused throughout the document and are accessed by using the var().

lessonsList.name: Miscellaneous Features
lessonsList.description: In this lesson, we will discuss some interesting CSS features such as dark and light mode property, CSS comments, text gradients and image effects that you can use to enhance your web pages.

topicList.name: Dark and light mode
Text Gradient
topicList.description: Text gradient in CSS allows the color transition in the text fonts. You can refer “Can I Use” website to check which browsers support this function

topicList.name: CSS Comments
topicList.description: CSS comments help to improve readability and make it more understandable. These comments are used to edit the source codes at a later date. CSS comment is written as /*Comments*/

topicList.name: Image Effects
topicList.description: In this topic to make it more understandable the colored image is converting into a grayscale image by using a CSS property named filter property. The filter property is mainly used to set the visual effect of images.

lessonsList.name: Advanced Selectors
lessonsList.description: The advanced selectors are the most important parts of CSS. They shape the CSS and determine how styles are to be applied to elements on a page. They can be general and apply to a large group of elements or be more specific and apply to only a single HTML element.

topicList.name: Child Combinator
topicList.description: The child combinator is used to to select the element that is the immediate child of the specified tag. It is denoted by “>”.

topicList.name: Adjacent Sibling Selector
topicList.description: The adjacent sibling selector is used to select the element that is adjacent to the specified tag.	It is represented by “+”

topicList.name: General Sibling Selector
topicList.description: The general sibling selector is used to select the element that are sibling of a specified element.

topicList.name: Pseudo Classes
topicList.description:
Pseudo classes are used to define a special state of an element. 
Example : When a user hovers over the element style of element is changed, or when a link is visited.
There are different kinds of pseudo classes in CSS namely hover, active, visited and link, but most commonly used pseudo classes are hover and active classes
Hover Pseudo Class :
This class is used to add a special effect on the element when a mouse hovers it.
Active Pseudo Class :
This class is used to select an element which is activated when the user clicks on it.

topicList.name: First and Last Child
topicList.description:
First Child Pseudo Class 
The first child selector is used to select those elements which are first class elements.
Last Child Pseudo Class 
The last child selector is used to select those elements which are the last class elements

topicList.name: nth child
topicList.description: nth-child() selector in CSS is used to match the elements based on their position in a group of siblings. It matches every element that is the nth child.

topicList.name: Attribute Selector
topicList.description: The  [attribute="value"] selector is used to select elements with a specified attribute and value.

topicList.name: Input Pseudo Classes
topicList.description:
As we know the pseudo-class is combined with CSS elements and is used to define the special states of elements. The input pseudo-class also plays an important role for the states of elements. The different kinds of input pseudo elements are given below:
a. Focus selector
The focus selector is used to target the focussed element, which means that the focussed element only shows a special state. 
Invalid Selector
b. The invalid selector allows you to select <input> elements that do not contain valid content, as determined by its type attribute.
c. Required Selector 
The required selector is used to select the required element with the required attribute and set the CSS property.
d. Disabled Selector
The disabled selector is used to select the disabled element.
e. In-range Selector
The in-range selector is used to select all elements that are given within a particular range value.
f. Enabled Selector
The enabled selector matches every enabled element

lessonsList.name: Flexbox Layout
lessonsList.description: As the name suggests, in the CSS flexbox layout items will “flex” in different sizes to easily format the HTML. It can be aligned in vertically and horizontally to make the responsive design easier. There are different properties used to align the items which you will learn in detail in the topics.

topicList.name: Flexbox Introduction
topicList.description: The Flexible Box Layout Module, makes it easier to design flexible responsive layout structure. The flex box is  defined with amanner  flex container in which it's siblings are arranged in a particular manner by using different flex properties.

topicList.name: Display flex
topicList.description: The display property is used to the flex to make the flex container more flexible. We can give it appropriate width, height and background to make it more visible.

topicList.name: Flex direction
topicList.description:
The flex-direction property defines in which direction the container wants to assemble the flex items or flex elements. 

The row is the default flex-direction, which moves the flex items from left to right. Also, there are other properties like row-reverse (right to left), column and column-reverse used to align the flex items in the flex container.

topicList.name: Flex Wrap
topicList.description:
The flex-wrap property specifies whether the flex items should wrap or not. 

The default value of flex-wrap is "no-wrap" and "wrap-reverse" is also used to wrap the flex items in reverse order.

topicList.name: Flex Order
topicList.description: The order property specifies the order of the flex items. The default value of each flex item is zero. And the order value is given in a number, which means that the applied value to the first flex item in the code does not have to appear as the first item in the layout.

topicList.name: Flex Grow
topicList.description:
The flex-grow property specifies how much a flex item will grow relative to the rest of the flex items.
The applied value must be a number, where the default value is 0.

topicList.name: Flex Shrink
topicList.description: The flex-shrink property specifies how much a flex item will shrink relative to the rest of the flex items. The value must be a number, the default value is 1.

topicList.name: Justify Content
topicList.description:
The justify-content property is used to align the flex lines. There are different properties used to align the contents in the flex as given below: 

a. Space Between
The space-between value displays the flex lines with equal space between them.

b. Space Around
The space-around value displays the flex lines with space before, between, and after them.

c. Centre
The centre value displays display the flex lines in the middle of the container.

d. Flex Start
The flex-start value displays the flex lines at the start of the container.

e. Flex End
The flex-end value displays the flex lines at the end of the container.

topicList.name: Align Items
topicList.description:
Align Items
The align-items property is used to align the flex items vertically. There are different properties used to align the items in the container namely :

a. Center Align
The centre value aligns the flex items in the middle of the container.

b. Flex Start
The flex-start value aligns the flex items at the top of the container.

c. Flex End
The flex-end value aligns the flex items at the bottom of the container.

d. Stretch 
The stretch value stretches the flex items to fill the container.

e. Baseline
The baseline value aligns the flex items such as their baselines aligns.

topicList.name: Align Content
topicList.description:
Align Content
The align-content property is used to align the flex lines. There are different properties used to align the contents in the flex as given below: 

a. Space Between
The space-between value displays the flex lines with equal space between them.

b. Space Around
The space-around value displays the flex lines with space before, between, and after them.

c. Centre
The centre value displays display the flex lines in the middle of the container.

d. Flex Start
The flex-start value displays the flex lines at the start of the container.

e. Flex End
The flex-end value displays the flex lines at the end of the container.

topicList.name: Align Self
topicList.description:
The align-self property in CSS is used to align the selected items in the flexible container in many different manners such as flex-end, centre, flex-start, etc.

a. Centre Align
This property is used to place the item at the centre of the flexible container.

b. Flex Start
The flex-start property is used to align the selected item at the beginning of the flexible container.

c. Flex End
The flex-end property is used to position the selected item at the end of the flexible container.

lessonsList.name: Pseudo Elements
lessonsList.description: Pseudo-elements are used to add special effects to  CSS selectors that enable you to style a specific part of the selected HTML element. Pseudo-elements are like virtual elements that we can treat as regular HTML elements.

topicList.name: Selection Pseudo Element
topicList.description: The selection CSS pseudo-element applies styles to the part of a document that has been highlighted by the user (such as clicking and dragging the mouse across text).

topicList.name: Styling First Letter and First Line Pseudo Element
topicList.description:
The first-letter pseudo-element is used to add a special style to the first letter of a text.
The first-line pseudo-element is used to add a special style to the first line of a paragraph.

topicList.name: Before and After Pseudo Element
topicList.description:
The before pseudo element is used to add some CSS property before an element when that element is called.
The after pseudo element is used to add some CSS property after an element when that element is called.

lessonsList.name: Browsers Work
lessonsList.description:
The web browser is at the heart of how we experience the internet. Every day, millions visit websites via browsers.

When you enter a Web address (URL) in your browser, this actually sends an HTTP command to the Web server directing it to fetch and transmit the requested Web page and display the information in your browser. It is what allows Web clients and Web servers to communicate with each other.

The Five major browsers  are Chrome, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.

topicList.name: Rendering Engines
topicList.description:
A rendering engine displays the web pages written in HTML in a way how you see with the web browsers. There are different rendering engines for different browsers as shown below:
a. Blink – Used in Google Chrome, and Opera browsers.
b. WebKit – Used in Safari browsers.
c. Gecko – Used in Mozilla Firefox browsers.
d. Trident – Used in Internet Explorer browsers.
e. EdgeHTML – Used in Edge browsers.
f. Presto – Legacy rendering engine for Opera.

topicList.name: Vendor Prefixes
topicList.description:
CSS vendor prefixes, also known as CSS browser prefixes, are a way for browser makers to add support for new CSS features before those features are fully supported in all browsers.

Here are some popular browsers and their corresponding identifiers:
-webki- = Google Chrome, Safari, Android
-moz- = Firefox
-o- = Opera
-ms- = Internet Explorer, Edge

lessonsList.name: Responsive Web Design Media Queries
lessonsList.description:
The use of mobile devices to surf the web is growing at an astronomical pace, but unfortunately much of the web isn't optimized for those mobile devices. Responsive web design responds to the needs of the users and the devices they're using. The layout changes based on the size and capabilities of the device.

Media queries are a key part of responsive web design, as they allow you to create different layouts depending on the size of the viewport, but they can also be used to detect other things about the environment your site is running on.

topicList.name: Responsive design
topicList.description: Responsive design is a way to put together a website so that it automatically scales its content and elements to match the screen size on which it is viewed. It keeps images from being larger than the screen width, and prevents visitors on mobile devices from needing to do extra work to read your content.

topicList.name: Media query and different checkpoints
topicList.description: A media query consists of a media type and zero or more expressions that match the type and conditions of a particular media feature such as device width or screen resolution. CSS checkpoints are points where the website content responds according to the device width, allowing you to show the best possible layout to the user.

lessonsList.name: Website Structuring
lessonsList.description:
Website structuring or site structuring refers to how the website is set up i.e. how the individual subpages are linked to one another. “A good structure means better crawling”, so you need to manage your website development through a perfect structuring. 

Through this lesson, you will learn how to structure a website with perfection. The related topics give you a detailed structuring of each section of the websites.

lessonsList.name: Grid Layout
lessonsList.description: CSS Grid is a powerful tool that allows for two-dimensional layouts to be created on the web which means it can handle both rows and columns, unlike flexbox which holds as a one-dimensional system. In this lesson, you will learn more about grid elements and it's element children's (grid items).

topicList.name: Introduction
topicList.description: The basic difference between CSS Grid Layout and CSS Flexbox Layout is that flexbox was designed for layout in one dimension - either a row or a column. Grid was designed for two-dimensional layout - rows, and columns at the same time.

topicList.name: Arranging rows and columns
topicList.description: We can arrange rows and columns by using the properties ‘grid-template-columns’ and ‘grid-template-rows’ after displaying the element as grid by ‘display’ property.

topicList.name: Grid column
topicList.description: The grid-column property specifies a grid item's size and location in a grid layout, and is a shorthand property for the following properties: ‘grid-column-start’ and ‘grid-column-end’.

topicList.name: Grid auto rows and grid template rows
topicList.description: The grid-auto-rows defines the size of grid rows that were created implicitly: it means that grid-auto-rows targets the rows that were not defined with grid-template-rows or grid-template-areas. The grid-template-rows property in CSS is used to set the number of rows and height of the rows in a grid. The values of grid-template-rows are space-separated, where each value represents the height of the row.

topicList.name: Grid template areas
topicList.description: The grid-template-areas property specifies areas within the grid layout. You can name grid items by using the grid-area property and then reference to the name in the grid-template-areas property. Each area is defined by apostrophes.

topicList.name: Align items in a grid
topicList.description: We can arrange and align-items in a grid using properties ‘align-items’ and ’ justify-items’ in common. We can also arrange items specifically for a grid using properties ‘align-self’ and ’ justify-self’.

topicList.name: Grid gap
topicList.description: The grid-gap property defines the size of the gap between the rows and columns in a grid layout and is a shorthand property for the following properties: ‘grid-row-gap’ and ‘grid-column-gap’

skillsList.name: Git & Gitlab
skillsList.description: Git is a Distributed Version Control System to track all the changes in the source code during the development of software. Whereas GitLab functions as a remote access to Git repositories that also helps to manage during the development cycle.

lessonsList.name: Git Basics
lessonsList.description:
Git is a Version Control System, that helps you document and store changes you made to your file throughout time. Every time you change something in your file and save it, you commit a change. 

VCS also gives you the ability to add comments to your changes, to keep things organized and later know to what state you'd like to return your file to before given change happens.

Due to its flexibility and distributed functionality for developers, it is also known as a Distributed Version Control System (DVCS).

topicList.name: Introduction
topicList.description:
Git is a service that provides remote access to Git repositories. In addition to hosting your code, the services provide additional features designed to manage the software development lifecycle. It records changes of a project and makes the ability to collaborate. 
Get possesses a  distributed version control system (DVCS) where the complete codebase including its full version history is mirrored on every developer's computer and also changes to files are tracked between computers.

topicList.name: Git and Installations
topicList.description:
Git is the most popular and actively maintained DVCS and is developed with most functionality, performance, security and flexibility that most teams and individual developers need.
i. macOS
If you have installed XCode (or it’s command-line tools), Git may already be installed
ii. Windows
https://gitforwindows.org/ in this site, click the download button,
Get the latest version and install in your system 
iii. Ubuntu
Enter these commands on your system terminal
Sudo apt-get update
Sudo apt-get install get 
Configuration:
Open your terminal and run these commands
git config ---global user.name “Your Name”
Git config ---global user.email “yrmail@example.com”

topicList.name: Different version control repository hosting services
topicList.description:
i. GitLab offers unlimited private repositories for unlimited contributors for unlimited file sizes for free. Although they may start to charge for files larger than 10GB in the future. It’s better for a private repository.  
ii. GitHub has integrated issue tracking that makes hunting and solving bugs easy. Each project's issues page can be filtered by closed issues, assignees, labels and milestones. Issues are also sortable by age, number of comments and update time.
iii. Bitbucket offers unlimited private repositories for free, as long as the number of members in a team is not larger than 5. In other words, it does not charge for each number of private repository, instead, it charges by the number of team members.

topicList.name: Creating a GitLab account
topicList.description:
i. Open GitLab website, https://gitlab.com/
ii. Click Register 
iii. Enter your personal information and register. Confirm the account from your mail account.

topicList.name: Create a repository
topicList.description:
i. Login GitLab account.
ii. Click on a new project or if you have one or more people click the new group.
iii. Enter the project name/group name and informations
iv. Add members from its left sidebar

topicList.name: Create a commit in cloud
topicList.description:
i. Login GitLab account.
ii. Click the new file.
iii. Give a file name and type your code. 
iv. And give a commit message in the commit box.
v. Now you can see the commit information. 
vi. If you need any edit in your code click the edit tab.
vii. After your editing commits your code.
viii. Now you can see the edit information as two or more versions.
ix. There you can have all details about your commit.

topicList.name: Clone a project
topicList.description:
Open your project in GitLab, there is a blue button named clone, That is used to clone your project into your system. Click the clone button and copy the HTTP method. Then open your terminal software/GitBash. And open your project folder(folder) using commands, then past your method link after, git clone command.
Example: Git clones https://gitlab.com/tutorial/tutorial-app.git 
Enter your username and password on the terminal. Now the project will be downloaded to your system with version history. Now you can open your project from your folder.

topicList.name: Saving changes to the repo
topicList.description:
Open your project in any text editor and make changes. Open your project folder on the terminal, then if you need to show your changes in your project, run git status.
Now you need to push your code to your GitLab server,  run git add on the terminal, then commit your code, git commit -m “ your message”. If you need to see your commit history, run this command on terminal git log now you can see the history. 
Push your changes to the git server using git push.
If you need to push your code again to the server before that pull the git server using git pull. This helps to download the latest changes to your system otherwise the git will be given a warning for pull in the git server.
If the terminal shows any conflict, firstly you must treat the conflict. Then push your code.

topicList.name: Git branches
topicList.description: If you need to treat a bug from your previous version, then select branches from your left sidebar, create a new branch. Then make your changes and go to files then select your branch and click to merge requests. After entering your details make a merge request.
